n men and women, and women's self-concept as Iranian Jewish women. Mother-daughter relationships, double standards for sons and daughters, marriage customs, the appeal of American forms of Jewish practices, social customs and pressures, and the alternate attraction to and critique of materialism and attention to outward appearance are discussed by the author and through the voices of her informants.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aIran -- Politics and government -- 1979-1997. 0aIranian Americans -- California -- Los Angeles -- Social life and customs. 0aIranian Americans -- Religious life -- California -- Los Angeles. 0aIranian AmericansxReligious lifezCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aIranian AmericanszCaliforniazLos AngelesxSocial life and customs. 0aJewish women -- Religious life -- California -- Los Angeles. 0aJewish women -- Religious life -- Iran. 0aJewish womenxReligious lifezCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aJewish womenxReligious lifezIran. 4aAmerican Studies : American Studies. 4aArea Studies : Middle East Studies. 4aJewish Studies : Jewish Studies. 4aReligion and Spirituality : American Religion. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438443850423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438443850/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles